Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as a221e432b030563430d1c1b32a6ebc010d3ba505

For IBM's p10bmc conf files, I had fairly recently made a change to use the device path that udev has instead of the OF_FULLNAME env var, with the intent being to have it be independent of the node name in the DTS.

That changed the path such that it didn't match your sed commands, for example: https://github.com/openbmc/openbmc/blob/master/meta-ibm/recipes-phosphor/sensors/phosphor-hwmon/p10bmc/obmc/hwmon/devices/platform/ahb/ahb--apb/ahb--apb--bus%401e78a000/1e78a400.i2c-bus/i2c-7/7-0052.conf  so those still need to be fixed too.

Notes:  There's a '--' in the path because yocto/bitbake doesn't let one have a colon in a directory name.  So it uses a '--' and then fixes it up in start_hwmon.sh.  At the time when I first looked into it, I tried to figure out why that was the case in bitbake but eventually gave up. If there's a better way to do that I'm all ears.

You said /sys/class/i2c-dev  are actually the only stable paths?  I don't think udev gives us any of those paths, but i wonder if we could just have start_hwmon.sh convert the /sys/devices path into a /sys/class/i2c-dev path and use that as the template arg to start the systemd service.  Maybe I can tackle that later.
I've moved the p10bmc config files as well now.

Here's Rainier's max31785 details:
```
# echo 7-0052 > bind
KERNEL[66.547135] add      /devices/platform/ahb/1e780000.apb/1e780000.apb:bus@1e78a000/1e78a400.i2c/i2c-7/7-0052/hwmon/hwmon9 (hwmon)
UDEV  [66.565114] add      /devices/platform/ahb/1e780000.apb/1e780000.apb:bus@1e78a000/1e78a400.i2c/i2c-7/7-0052/hwmon/hwmon9 (hwmon)
KERNEL[66.756762] bind     /devices/platform/ahb/1e780000.apb/1e780000.apb:bus@1e78a000/1e78a400.i2c/i2c-7/7-0052 (i2c)
UDEV  [66.756835] bind     /devices/platform/ahb/1e780000.apb/1e780000.apb:bus@1e78a000/1e78a400.i2c/i2c-7/7-0052 (i2c)
```

So the '.i2c-bus' just needs to be '.i2c' instead on p10bmc's conf file paths.
IBM signed off.  meta-facebook seems reasonable.  Other machines impacted aren't highly maintained.
